-- Market Chatter- Corporate finance press digest
-- 
-- Wed Apr 16, 2014 11:44PM EDT
-- None



April 17 (Reuters) - The following corporate finance-related stories were reported by media:

* Cereal maker Post Holdings Inc <POST.N> is close to a deal to acquire eggs and dairy producer and distributor Michael Foods Group Inc [MFODSM.UL] for $2.5 billion, prevailing over a rival bid from Tyson Foods Inc <TSN.N>, said a person familiar with the matter. [ID:nL2N0N81QI]  * Warburg Pincus LLC [WP.UL] is in advanced talks to acquire Electronic Funds Source LLC in a deal that could value the transportation services payments company at more than $1 billion, according to people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL6N0N33VP]  * Ahli United Bank <AUBB.BH>, Bahrain's largest lender, is evaluating a sale or a merger with a rival bank in a potential $5 billion deal, several bankers familiar with the situation said. [ID:nL6N0N74KQ]  * PACC Offshore Services Holdings could raise at least S$388.27 million ($310.5 million) after pricing its initial public offering near the bottom of the pricing range indicated earlier, two sources with knowledge of the matter said. [ID:nL3N0N8573]  * Discovery Communications <DISCA.O> has dropped out of bidding to buy Britain's free-to-air Channel 5, according to two sources familiar with the matter. [ID:nL2N0N82DU]  * Germany's ThyssenKrupp <TKAG.DE> has agreed a 2 billion euro ($2.76 billion), three-year revolving credit facility to replace an existing 2.5 billion euro facility that was due to mature in July, banking sources said. [ID:nL6N0N84K0]  * Australian developer Meriton Group is considering a A$3 billion ($2.81 billion) offer from a Chinese developer for half its apartment business, according to a media report, highlighting increasing Chinese interest in Australia's housing market. [ID:nL3N0N8585]  * Britain's veteran entrepreneurs Nick Leslau and Sir Tom Hunter are set to return to the stock market with a flotation of property assets worth 1.5 billion pounds, the Financial Times reported, citing people familiar with the matter. (http://r.reuters.com/kez58v)  * Chemtura Corp <CHMT.N> plans to sell its agrochemicals business to Platform Specialty Products Corp <PAH.N> for about $1 billion, the Wall Street Journal reported, citing people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL3N0N90R6]  For the deals of the day click on [DEALS/]